value.0: A tall, strong and strapping man. He considers you with a careful, steady eye, but offers a warming smile as you approach him.
The no-nonsense dwarf's muscles bulge from years standing over the forge and anvil. His skin is dusted with soot, and unless you caught him on a rare break he glistens with a sheen of sweat.
The man's clothes are covered in wood shavings and the occasional scrap of feather. He looks at you a bit impatiently; perhaps eager to get back to his work.
The well-dressed gnome puffs on his pipe while he waits on you to make up your mind.
Wait, did you just see her over there? Oh.... twins. The twin librarians work diligently keeping the book shelves neat and organized.

This finely styled knee-length coat is trimmed with elegant embroidery work. It can be dressed up for the more formal gentleman, or simplified for the more common man depending on the fabrics, accessories, and colors chosen. Styles are available for both men and women.
Simple and elegant; this style of dress is made from lighter weight fabrics that gather and drape to flatter most any frame. It comes in a wide variety of colors.

For the more elegant and conservative Lady; this ensemble is generally made with heavier weighted fabrics. It is a piece that must be custom tailored for each individual, and as such you can be guaranteed to always be the most regal occupant in any room.

This basic and feminine daily wear is made to be comfortable for working; or relaxing. The overall style can be made more formal with elegant fabrics, colors and accessories; or worn simply and understated.
This basic and male daily wear can be altered slightly to also be comfortable for women. It combines sturdy and protective leathers with comfortable, and breathable cloths.
Riappi is a cheerful looking halfling, with chestnut skin and hair. She seems to be a people person, or at the very least, enjoys the job she has held for years.

Aluvard is well known to be one of the shops proprietors. He strokes his neatly trimmed beard while he looks you over as a potential customer. Likely he is using his years of experience to size you up, and judge your style; before any greeting has even been exchanged. The clothing he wears is sort of business casual; meant to be professional while also comfortable to work in all day. You can tell at a glance it is very well made. The fabrics work well together. The cuts of the pattern are precise, and lay well to the man's frame. The stitching of the seams is completely invisible. Dare you hope it is an example of his own workmanship?

Alaundo (-22 to 76 DR) himself was the son of minor traitor against the Calishite state. He began making organized recorded prophecies in -2 DR, when he left his family to live as a hermit and shepherd in the Dales (it is unrecorded which one). His prophecies were recorded in private over the next seventy-five years. Legend says that Alaundo saw a vision of his own impending death, so he journeyed to Candlekeep to donate his records for posterity, arriving in 75 DR. He died there, almost unmourned, of a plague the next year. The sages at the library were so amazed by the accuracy of the predictions that starting in 82 DR, the monks there began a never-ending "Chant of the Unfulfilled Prophecies" which has continued uninterrupted to this day. All of Alaundo's books have been committed to memory by the thirty monks devoted to the task. As a prophecy comes to pass, the monks remove it from their chant.

Candlekeep is a many towered fortress library that stands on a crag, looking down upon the Sea of Swords. The library is filled with books and scrolls of knowledge, and it was the home of the great seer Alaundo, who foresaw the coming of the Bhaalspawn. To gain entry to the halls of wisdom, a visitor must gift the library collection with a new tome of immense value.

Knowledge, particularly the raw knowledge of ideas, is supreme. An idea has no weight, but it can move mountains. The greatest gift of humankind, an idea outweighs anything made by mortal hands. Knowledge is power and must be used with care, but hiding it away from others is never a good thing. Stifle no new ideas, no matter how false and crazed they seem; rather, let them be heard and considered.

Never slay a singer, nor stand by as others do so. Spread knowledge wherever it is prudent to do so. Curb and deny falsehoods, rumor, and deceitful tales whenever you encounter them. Write or copy lore of great value at least once a year and give it away. Sponsor and teach bards, scribes, and record keepers. Spread truth and knowledge so that all folk know more. Never deliver a message falsely or incompletely. Teach reading and writing to those who ask (if your time permits), and charge no fee for the teaching.
